This paper deals with cryptographic protocols and information theory, which are both subcategories of computer science. The use of DH key-exchange and verification methods suggest that the paper falls under the category of cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also deals with the transfer of information, which is a topic covered in information theory (cs.IT). The use of random sequences and probability events suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper proposes a variation to an existing protocol, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of distributed systems (cs.DS). Finally, the paper proposes a method to verify the correctness of the procedure, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of computer engineering (cs.CE).
